    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-06T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-06T10:00:00-05:00" n="2"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5161: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1"
                            type="to">Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-06T11:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 6, 1932—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>170. For the Minister. Your May 5, 9 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Department has had no report from official sources regarding incident on
                        Settlement border to which you refer.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>On basis of newspaper reports, it would seem inadvisable to Department to
                        remove 31st Infantry immediately on the heels of that incident.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>With regard to other factors, the Secretary of State is now on his way
                            home;<note n="1" xml:id="d2fn1">Mr. <persName
                                corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">Stimson</persName> was in Europe
                            attending the General Disarmament Conference at Geneva.</note> the
                        Department desires to discuss with him this question and its relation to
                        other questions; therefore probably no action until after his arrival.
                        Inform Commander-in-Chief of all of the above.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Can you inform Department how many (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) British and
                            (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) American soldiers, marines, landable
                        bluejackets and volunteers are now present at Shanghai?<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d2fn2">
                            <p>The Consul General replied in telegram No. 241, May 13, 1 p.m.: <list>
                                    <item>“(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) Present British forces ashore:
                                        3,049 plus 200 marines and bluejackets immediately landable
                                        if necessary.</item>
                                    <item>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) Present American forces ashore:
                                        31st Infantry 1,279, marines 1,412, plus 200 American
                                        marines and bluejackets immediately landable if necessary.
                                        Shanghai volunteer corps, all nationalities, 2,239. Grand
                                        total, 8,379.” (793.94/5218).</item>
                                </list>
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Please see that Department is informed immediately when state of emergency
                        is lifted.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CWR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
